  • The disease process results in crypt hyperplasia and villous atrophy.

Symptoms

Most commonly asymptomatic; but patients will show signs of malabsorption.
Many and will be diagnosed upon evaluation for macrocytic anaemia. (due to malabsorption).
Mouth ulcers, angular stomatits.

If symptomatic, diarrhoea, steatorrhoea, abdominal pain and weight loss in severe disease.
Can present at any age.
Female predominance. Peak is at 40-50 years.

Complications

Osteoporosis
parasaesthesia, ataxia, polyneuropathy.
Associated with autoimmune diseases: IBD, primary biliary cholangitis, chonic liver disease, ILD, epilepsy.

Diagnosis:

gold standard: small bowel biopsy.
Serology is very useful : endomysial and tissue transglutaminase antibodies.

Pulmonary eosinophilia (PE)

Pulmonary eosinophilia (PE) is defined as the infiltration of eosinophils into the lung tissue; Source

PE can be divided into primary and secondary based on causes:
| Primary PE | Secondary PE |
| -------------------------------- | --------------------------------------- |
| Acute eosinophilic pneumonia | Allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis |
| Chronic eosinophilic pneumonia | Parasites |
| EGPA | Medications |
| Hypereosinophilic syndrome (HES) | Radiation effects |
| | Malignancies |

[!INFO] Commonest cause of pulmonary eosinophilia is parasitic infestation.

Drugs causing PE

  • NSAIDS, aspirin
  • ACE inhibitors
  • TMP-SMX
  • others

Loffler syndrome / Loeffler syndrome

#2021SBR-NOV Q13

Also called simple pulmonary eosinophilia

  • Acute (<2 weeks), mild ilness(just fever and cough)
  • with transient pulmonary radiographic opacities and
  • peripheral blood eosinophilia associated with
  • allergic reaction to intestinal parasites, commonly described with Ascariasis and Strongyloidiasis.

Resolves spotaneously!

If the course is more prolonged, the disease is called prolonged pulmonary eosinophilia.
